## 3. Climate Change Impacts on Harp Seals and Ice-Associated Species

### 3.1 Dependence on Sea Ice for Breeding

Harp seals rely on seasonal sea ice as breeding platforms. Their life history strategies are adapted to fluctuations in ice quantity and quality, making them sensitive to changes in sea ice conditions ([Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

### 3.2 Neonatal Mortality and Ice Conditions

Studies have demonstrated a strong correlation between sea ice cover and harp seal pup mortality. Specifically, lighter ice years correspond with significantly higher neonatal mortality rates due to factors such as:

- Interrupted nursing
- Starvation
- Cold stress
- Crushing by shifting ice floes

For instance, in 2010, the Gulf of St. Lawrence experienced the lightest ice cover on record, coinciding with near 100% mortality of harp seal pups in the region ([Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

### 3.3 Influence of the North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO)

The NAO, a climatic phenomenon affecting atmospheric pressure patterns, influences sea ice dynamics in harp seal breeding areas. Negative NAO phases lead to reduced ice cover and increased pup mortality. Retrospective analyses indicate that harp seal populations have fluctuated in synchrony with NAO trends and associated ice conditions, suggesting climate variability as a key driver of population dynamics ([Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

### 3.4 Long-Term Declines in Sea Ice and Population Trends

Since 1979, satellite data reveal a decline in sea ice cover of up to 6% per decade in harp seal breeding regions across the North Atlantic. This trend correlates with observed decreases in pup production and increased neonatal mortality, raising concerns about the long-term viability of harp seal populations ([Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

### 3.5 Other Ice-Associated Seals

Species such as hooded seals (Cystophora cristata) share similar vulnerabilities due to their dependence on sea ice for breeding. The Northeast Atlantic hooded seal stock has declined by 85–90% over the last 40–60 years, highlighting the severity of climate impacts on ice-dependent seals ([Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

