## 4. Impacts on Seals in the Arctic and Subarctic Regions

### 4.1 Ribbon, Spotted, and Harbor Seals

These species inhabit seasonally ice-covered waters in the Bering Sea and Sea of Okhotsk. They depend on sea ice for critical life events such as pupping, breeding, and molting. Recent rapid warming in the Arctic has led to declines in the physical condition of these seals, which could negatively affect their populations ([NOAA Fisheries, 2021](https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/feature-story/condition-seals-declined-during-rapid-warming-alaska)).

### 4.2 Ecological and Metabolic Considerations

Ribbon, spotted, and harbor seals are upper trophic level predators with high metabolic rates. Changes in sea ice and prey availability can disrupt their energy balance and feeding efficiency, potentially leading to population declines ([NOAA Fisheries, 2021](https://www.fisheries.noaa.gov/feature-story/condition-seals-declined-during-rapid-warming-alaska)).

