## 5. Broader Ecological and Conservation Considerations

### 5.1 Shifts in Species Distributions and Ecosystem Dynamics

Climate change drives shifts in the distribution and abundance of marine species, including seals and their prey. These changes alter food web structures and ecosystem functions, with cascading effects on seal populations. For example, reductions in penguin populations due to climate stress increase leopard seal predation pressure on fur seal pups ([University of Barcelona, 2021](https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2021/12/211202113448.htm)).

### 5.2 Adaptability and Resilience

While some seal species exhibit adaptability through dietary flexibility or range shifts, the pace of environmental change often outstrips their capacity to adjust. Slow southward migration of Antarctic fur seals and the inability of ice-dependent seals to breed without adequate ice platforms exemplify these constraints ([University of Barcelona, 2021](https://phys.org/news/2021-12-climate-crisis-affect-antarctic-fur.html); [Johnston et al., 2012](https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0029158)).

### 5.3 Human Impacts and Management Needs

Human activities, including hunting, by-catch, and krill fisheries, compound climate-related stressors. Effective management strategies must integrate climate projections and species-specific ecological requirements to mitigate cumulative impacts. For Antarctic fur seals, managing krill fisheries year-round is essential to sustain populations ([University of Barcelona, 2021](https://phys.org/news/2021-12-climate-crisis-affect-antarctic-fur.html)).

