## 7. Conclusion and Opinion

The evidence clearly demonstrates that climate change exerts profound, multifaceted impacts on seal populations globally. Ice-dependent species such as harp and hooded seals face existential threats from diminishing sea ice, which directly compromises breeding success and pup survival. Antarctic fur seals, while somewhat adaptable through dietary shifts, suffer reproductive declines linked to krill scarcity and increased predation pressures exacerbated by ecosystem imbalances.

Given the slow pace of natural adaptation and range shifts, proactive, science-based management is imperative. This includes regulating fisheries that compete with seals for prey, protecting critical habitats, and integrating climate projections into conservation planning. The complexity of these challenges demands coordinated international efforts, continuous monitoring, and adaptive management frameworks.

In my assessment, seals serve as sentinel species reflecting the broader health of marine ecosystems under climate stress. Their declining populations underscore the urgency of mitigating climate change and implementing robust conservation strategies to preserve marine biodiversity and ecosystem function.

